1
00:04:59,807 --> 00:05:02,468
[SPEAKER_03]: blind you check check one two three one two three.

2
00:05:08,949 --> 00:05:10,710
[SPEAKER_03]: Check check one two three one two three.

3
00:05:15,451 --> 00:05:17,331
[SPEAKER_03]: I check one that one's a little hot.

4
00:05:18,531 --> 00:05:19,972
[SPEAKER_03]: Check one two three one two three.

5
00:05:30,115 --> 00:05:31,565
[SPEAKER_02]: Check, check, one, two, three, okay.

6
00:06:12,417 --> 00:06:14,819
Okay, we're gonna let the magic happen

7
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:40,921
[SPEAKER_03]: Good evening, friends and neighbors.

8
00:06:41,001 --> 00:06:47,386
[SPEAKER_03]: My name is Terry E. Carter, and I direct elder services at our beloved West Metro Community Center.

9
00:06:47,766 --> 00:06:53,550
[SPEAKER_03]: Welcome to another live monthly presentation of Fresh Fridays, Words and Music.

10
00:06:53,610 --> 00:07:01,456
[SPEAKER_03]: We are rebranded, cobbled and sanded for May, an opportunity to celebrate mothers, doers, and achievers.

11
00:07:01,936 --> 00:07:08,421
[SPEAKER_03]: We're happy to be with you tonight with another critical conversation that keeps us on track

12
00:07:09,432 --> 00:07:13,354
[SPEAKER_03]: with our culture keeping duties here at 111 Arlington Street.

13
00:07:13,915 --> 00:07:27,563
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks as always to assistance from the Medford Arts Council, a member of the Massachusetts Cultural Council, and to the generous members, friends, and supporters of this invaluable neighborhood resource.

14
00:07:28,783 --> 00:07:41,155
[SPEAKER_03]: It appears that spring is threatening, but hasn't yet made a total commitment to those perfect New England summer days of soft wind, sunny skies, and a warming trend.

15
00:07:41,653 --> 00:07:48,897
[SPEAKER_03]: So that said, we want to remind you to stay healthy, be mindful of the flu and COVID and RSV.

16
00:07:49,217 --> 00:07:52,338
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess the hantavirus is around on some of the cruise ships.

17
00:07:52,378 --> 00:07:54,359
[SPEAKER_03]: So you want to stay clear of that.

18
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:59,002
[SPEAKER_03]: And of course, allergy concerns and pollen counts are escalating.

19
00:07:59,522 --> 00:08:02,203
[SPEAKER_03]: Masking is welcomed, but not required.

20
00:08:02,864 --> 00:08:09,387
[SPEAKER_03]: And as I continue to stress, we're just happy to continue sponsoring live programming here at the WMCC.

21
00:08:09,948 --> 00:08:12,093
[SPEAKER_03]: and glad to see y'all coming through the doors.

22
00:08:12,153 --> 00:08:14,218
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you so much for being here.

23
00:08:15,332 --> 00:08:35,909
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks also to our other event sponsor, Kevin Harrington is back there from Medford Community Media, and he is consistently guiding us as we broadcast to you via Medford Community Media, channels nine for Comcast and 47 for Verizon, as well as on the MCM YouTube channel.

24
00:08:36,290 --> 00:08:42,035
[SPEAKER_03]: If you're out there watching on your electronic devices or your television, welcome to the show.

25
00:08:43,118 --> 00:08:53,983
[SPEAKER_03]: So before we get into the main business for the evening, I do want to make note of the change that has occurred in our original program for tonight due to a recent family loss.

26
00:08:54,063 --> 00:09:06,848
[SPEAKER_03]: Terry will certainly bring her back when the timing is right.

27
00:09:09,044 --> 00:09:22,055
[SPEAKER_03]: Last month, we were able to educate and entertain with Stephen Smitty Smith's The Elephant in the Room, a growing small business centered on exploring conversations about race and social justice.

28
00:09:22,515 --> 00:09:25,378
[SPEAKER_03]: We also had a musical nod to Poetry Month.

29
00:09:25,758 --> 00:09:33,081
[SPEAKER_03]: with the Ally Project, featuring yours truly, along with Jonathan Fagan, Greg Toro, and Gordon Engelgeier.

30
00:09:33,201 --> 00:09:40,364
[SPEAKER_03]: If you missed it, look for the show on Medford Community Media's program archive or on their YouTube page.

31
00:09:40,864 --> 00:09:42,345
[SPEAKER_03]: It really was a heck of a show.

32
00:09:42,825 --> 00:09:50,388
[SPEAKER_03]: We've got some more great events coming, including the 2026 Jazz Festival in August, so stay tuned.

33
00:09:51,048 --> 00:09:52,529
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, so I pivot.

34
00:09:53,373 --> 00:09:56,954
[SPEAKER_03]: for this evening's program is probably overdue.

35
00:09:57,715 --> 00:10:06,558
[SPEAKER_03]: Our very gracious and admittedly last-minute guests are by no means strangers, but you don't always get to see them in this particular light.

36
00:10:07,298 --> 00:10:18,663
[SPEAKER_03]: Please say hello to WMCC Executive Director Lisa Crossman, the queenly wave, and Board President Melinda Walsh-Reagan,

37
00:10:21,607 --> 00:10:28,711
[SPEAKER_03]: Each comes with a long resume of extensive experience and dedicated service to this community.

38
00:10:29,171 --> 00:10:31,133
[SPEAKER_03]: I won't go into great detail here.

39
00:10:31,233 --> 00:10:34,775
[SPEAKER_03]: Much of it will come to light as we have a friendly chat.

40
00:10:35,575 --> 00:10:44,961
[SPEAKER_03]: Suffice it to say that I work with some incredible people that have really grown and developed this organization in countless significant ways.

41
00:10:45,681 --> 00:10:53,209
[SPEAKER_03]: So as is my custom in hosting these evenings for you, I like to share a bit of verse to shape what we're going to get into.

42
00:10:53,729 --> 00:10:58,494
[SPEAKER_03]: I first shared this piece at our 90th anniversary gala last December.

43
00:10:59,055 --> 00:11:02,358
[SPEAKER_03]: For those of you who were there, I think it really hit home.

44
00:11:02,879 --> 00:11:05,621
[SPEAKER_03]: You know by now that I believe that poetry should

45
00:11:06,362 --> 00:11:09,047
[SPEAKER_03]: above all things, be accessible and inclusive.

46
00:11:09,508 --> 00:11:12,994
[SPEAKER_03]: And sometimes a poem is crafted for an occasion or a movement.

47
00:11:13,394 --> 00:11:15,057
[SPEAKER_03]: That is definitely the case tonight.

48
00:11:15,097 --> 00:11:17,542
[SPEAKER_03]: This piece is called The Center of It All.

49
00:11:19,070 --> 00:11:23,731
[SPEAKER_03]: By nature, this is a neighborhood story with testimonies and allegory.

50
00:11:23,911 --> 00:11:28,352
[SPEAKER_03]: Everyone needs a second home, like a poet needs to write a poem.

51
00:11:29,012 --> 00:11:33,413
[SPEAKER_03]: The men of the village made a pact to turn their vision toward actual fact.

52
00:11:33,733 --> 00:11:39,115
[SPEAKER_03]: It may have started as just for the brothers, but the notion grew to a place for others.

53
00:11:39,575 --> 00:11:48,457
[SPEAKER_03]: Boys and girls, women and men, by the wiser stroke of the founder's pen, a place to foster community where everyone finds opportunity.

54
00:11:49,337 --> 00:11:53,858
[SPEAKER_03]: So now we're here, 90 years young, climbing the ladder rung by rung.

55
00:11:53,878 --> 00:11:58,579
[SPEAKER_03]: We celebrate our local leaders, artists, scholars, and garden seeders.

56
00:11:59,059 --> 00:12:00,160
[SPEAKER_03]: It hasn't been easy.

57
00:12:00,400 --> 00:12:01,520
[SPEAKER_03]: To that we admit.

58
00:12:01,960 --> 00:12:03,901
[SPEAKER_03]: In every peach there is a pit.

59
00:12:04,421 --> 00:12:06,161
[SPEAKER_03]: We've had to fight to stay alive.

60
00:12:06,681 --> 00:12:08,882
[SPEAKER_03]: Before you advance, you must survive.

61
00:12:09,462 --> 00:12:15,205
[SPEAKER_03]: From that old army barracks at 111, the present address almost feels like heaven.

62
00:12:15,665 --> 00:12:19,647
[SPEAKER_03]: The seniors gather to lunch and meet, they exercise on tired feet.

63
00:12:20,188 --> 00:12:24,470
[SPEAKER_03]: The kids come in right after school, they try to be so very cool.

64
00:12:24,950 --> 00:12:29,913
[SPEAKER_03]: Cell phones and computer time after they make their snacks in slime.

65
00:12:30,613 --> 00:12:32,716
[SPEAKER_03]: The energy is quite contagious.

66
00:12:32,896 --> 00:12:34,819
[SPEAKER_03]: Behavior borders on the outrageous.

67
00:12:35,219 --> 00:12:39,144
[SPEAKER_03]: We try to take it all in stride or maybe just make them go outside.

68
00:12:39,925 --> 00:12:43,310
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the game we used to play at Duggar Park back in the day.

69
00:12:43,630 --> 00:12:47,956
[SPEAKER_03]: We've worked to bring that notion back for beige and brown and white and black.

70
00:12:48,877 --> 00:12:58,300
[SPEAKER_03]: So now we're here at 90 years young, still climbing that ladder rung by rung, staying strong through partnership, serving the people that others may skip.

71
00:12:59,301 --> 00:13:03,382
[SPEAKER_03]: WMCC for short, proud and strong is my report.

72
00:13:03,722 --> 00:13:08,404
[SPEAKER_03]: We'll open the door and turn on the lights to one of Medford's historic sites.

73
00:13:08,964 --> 00:13:10,164
[SPEAKER_03]: Charity begins at home.

74
00:13:10,265 --> 00:13:12,125
[SPEAKER_03]: Find your wallet while I write this poem.

75
00:13:12,545 --> 00:13:13,866
[SPEAKER_03]: You may also write a check.

76
00:13:14,706 --> 00:13:16,167
[SPEAKER_03]: I digress, but what the heck.

77
00:13:16,247 --> 00:13:20,289
[SPEAKER_03]: We need the money, but even more, we want to see you come through the door.

78
00:13:20,349 --> 00:13:24,651
[SPEAKER_03]: We want to see you on Friday nights with words and music that offers delight.

79
00:13:25,211 --> 00:13:32,274
[SPEAKER_03]: We want to see you come for lunch, not only when Ketley dresses things up and Norma serves cheer in a festive cup.

80
00:13:33,075 --> 00:13:38,137
[SPEAKER_03]: We're a place for history, culture, and art in a great neighborhood of loving hearts.

81
00:13:38,557 --> 00:13:43,780
[SPEAKER_03]: We started the journey in 35, so many folks no longer alive.

82
00:13:44,563 --> 00:13:46,765
[SPEAKER_03]: But you're still here, so make it count.

83
00:13:47,066 --> 00:13:49,068
[SPEAKER_03]: And don't let us fail for any amount.

84
00:13:49,128 --> 00:13:54,894
[SPEAKER_03]: Let's still be around in 10 more years, 100 through all the pain and tears.

85
00:13:55,295 --> 00:13:58,919
[SPEAKER_03]: We celebrate with you today, but make a promise not to stray.

86
00:13:59,019 --> 00:14:01,622
[SPEAKER_03]: Gather your tribe and make a pact.

87
00:14:02,002 --> 00:14:03,784
[SPEAKER_03]: Don't let anything hold you back.

88
00:14:04,485 --> 00:14:09,170
[SPEAKER_03]: This neighborhood is certainly changed, much that we knew has been rearranged.

89
00:14:09,590 --> 00:14:16,437
[SPEAKER_03]: Maybe you own, you may be a renter, but everyone's welcome here at the center.

90
00:14:20,921 --> 00:14:21,882
[SPEAKER_03]: Good, good, good, good, good.

91
00:14:23,003 --> 00:14:24,825
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good, very good, okay.

92
00:14:25,573 --> 00:14:33,000
[SPEAKER_03]: So now that the table is set, let's talk about it with my esteemed colleagues in this beloved place we call home.

93
00:14:34,602 --> 00:14:40,788
[SPEAKER_03]: Lisa, what is your original connection to Medford, and what other places have you or do you call home?

94
00:14:42,733 --> 00:14:48,455
[SPEAKER_07]: So my original connection is through the Coleman's who lived on Harvard Ave.

95
00:14:49,015 --> 00:14:57,678
[SPEAKER_07]: And their daughter, Danielle, she's my best friend, met her in college, out in Central Mass over at Fitchburg State College when it was that.

96
00:14:59,278 --> 00:15:05,059
[SPEAKER_07]: and started coming out here on weekends and went to basketball games.

97
00:15:05,259 --> 00:15:15,821
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we came to July 4th celebration in the back and we used to walk the streets at night and everyone was out.

98
00:15:15,882 --> 00:15:17,162
[SPEAKER_07]: Is that the way you want to say it?

99
00:15:19,002 --> 00:15:22,963
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, because there's a lot of walkers here, so you know what I'm talking about.

100
00:15:23,583 --> 00:15:23,863
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

101
00:15:24,924 --> 00:15:31,029
[SPEAKER_07]: So just going out for a stroll, seeing what's going on, saying hello to whoever might be out.

102
00:15:31,250 --> 00:15:36,194
[SPEAKER_07]: And that's when I got to know names, streets, and things that were going on.

103
00:15:37,755 --> 00:15:39,777
[SPEAKER_07]: And yes, she's still my best friend.

104
00:15:39,857 --> 00:15:42,559
[SPEAKER_07]: This is, what, 30 years later now?

105
00:15:43,560 --> 00:15:45,161
[SPEAKER_07]: Her family is my family.

106
00:15:45,622 --> 00:15:51,026
[SPEAKER_07]: And so Medford is a special place for me because the people I love are from here.

107
00:15:53,268 --> 00:15:58,833
[SPEAKER_07]: And then, so for me, home was, I grew up in Central Mass, so Leominster was where I grew up.

108
00:16:00,174 --> 00:16:03,737
[SPEAKER_07]: Moved to Lunenburg, Whelan Park, if you're, if you know, you know.

109
00:16:03,757 --> 00:16:06,820
[SPEAKER_03]: We used to have our church picnic there at Whelan Park.

110
00:16:07,926 --> 00:16:09,566
[SPEAKER_07]: So that was home.

111
00:16:10,907 --> 00:16:12,667
[SPEAKER_07]: And now we call Malden home.

112
00:16:12,727 --> 00:16:13,287
[SPEAKER_07]: We love it.

113
00:16:13,347 --> 00:16:16,328
[SPEAKER_07]: We've been there for just about 10 years now.

114
00:16:16,988 --> 00:16:17,408
[SPEAKER_07]: Love it.

115
00:16:17,628 --> 00:16:21,129
[SPEAKER_07]: And in Maine, Wells, Maine, we would also call home.

116
00:16:22,049 --> 00:16:25,770
[SPEAKER_07]: It's the last piece of where our family kind of grew up together.

117
00:16:25,970 --> 00:16:27,011
[SPEAKER_07]: Wonderful, wonderful.

118
00:16:28,191 --> 00:16:33,612
[SPEAKER_03]: How did your determination to come work here at the community center, how did that all come together?

119
00:16:38,206 --> 00:16:39,967
[SPEAKER_07]: I wouldn't call it determination.

120
00:16:40,067 --> 00:16:45,590
[SPEAKER_07]: I would call it divine intervention because it was during the pandemic.

121
00:16:46,050 --> 00:16:47,191
[SPEAKER_07]: I was unemployed.

122
00:16:47,211 --> 00:16:53,014
[SPEAKER_07]: I was at home and I hadn't worked for a year, which once I began working, we had a family business.

123
00:16:53,174 --> 00:16:57,416
[SPEAKER_07]: Once I began working at 14, 15, I never stopped working.

124
00:16:57,597 --> 00:16:58,417
[SPEAKER_07]: You and me both.

125
00:16:59,887 --> 00:17:19,245
[SPEAKER_07]: So I was at home, and Stephen Douglas, who is a friend of Daniel Coleman, the neighbors, he had stopped by the house and mentioned the organization and what was going on, and there was space on the board, and would I join, and it started from there.

126
00:17:19,285 --> 00:17:23,008
[SPEAKER_07]: It started as a board member interested to kind of

127
00:17:23,520 --> 00:17:34,447
[SPEAKER_07]: get my feet wet again, get the gears turning, and I really felt like my skills and experience could add value to the situation that was going on.

128
00:17:34,547 --> 00:17:36,268
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, very good, very good.

129
00:17:37,149 --> 00:17:46,035
[SPEAKER_03]: Did you discuss the idea with anybody, or did you present the idea to anybody, and what was their initial reaction, you're gonna go work at the community center?

130
00:17:47,338 --> 00:17:58,849
[SPEAKER_07]: I didn't, it kind of was an open conversation with people in the room and we kind of threw it out there and of course my best friend's like absolutely she would be great, but it was

131
00:18:00,121 --> 00:18:01,921
[SPEAKER_07]: It wasn't my plan.

132
00:18:01,941 --> 00:18:09,303
[SPEAKER_07]: I had an intention of doing my own business, and I had been planning that, and that was the plan.

133
00:18:09,743 --> 00:18:17,445
[SPEAKER_07]: But I also had been on this spiritual walk, and it was the first time I'm listening, and I'm following what I hear.

134
00:18:18,045 --> 00:18:26,207
[SPEAKER_07]: And I had some really great interviews, really great opportunities, but just the money wasn't right, and things weren't right.

135
00:18:26,267 --> 00:18:27,467
[SPEAKER_07]: The free time wasn't right.

136
00:18:28,372 --> 00:18:52,829
[SPEAKER_07]: and I turned down something that I couldn't believe I was turning down, but it was just like, they didn't meet me where I needed them to meet me, and I didn't know what I was gonna do, and then here comes Steven, pulling through the door, and here comes this opportunity, and it started out as just a board opportunity, but some things had gone on in the organization, and the executive director had,

137
00:18:53,810 --> 00:19:02,519
[SPEAKER_07]: had to leave quite quickly and I said I would fill in and she left on a Friday and I said I'd be there on Monday and I'm still here.

138
00:19:04,850 --> 00:19:07,251
[SPEAKER_03]: I know that story very well, as a matter of fact.

139
00:19:08,612 --> 00:19:12,354
[SPEAKER_03]: But you said, you used the term divine intervention.

140
00:19:12,374 --> 00:19:19,538
[SPEAKER_03]: I would definitely second that notion, because it was a divine intervention for you to come and work here.

141
00:19:20,058 --> 00:19:21,098
[SPEAKER_03]: I really believe that.

142
00:19:22,379 --> 00:19:30,143
[SPEAKER_03]: Melinda, if I can ask you about working in Medford and establishing a great love for this community, can you tell us how that all began?

143
00:19:31,543 --> 00:19:36,326
[SPEAKER_00]: So when I went to school, and so I grew up in Medford, right?

144
00:19:36,766 --> 00:19:42,909
[SPEAKER_00]: And my family home was actually kind of closer to where City Hall is, just on the other side of 93, like you're heading to Malden.

145
00:19:43,689 --> 00:19:51,393
[SPEAKER_00]: But by happenstance, when it came time to enroll in kindergarten, I joined a program that ran out of the Hervey School.

146
00:19:51,954 --> 00:19:56,776
[SPEAKER_00]: So I, you know, bused from home to the Hervey School.

147
00:19:57,416 --> 00:19:59,958
[SPEAKER_00]: And like, so K through five, growing up,

148
00:20:00,578 --> 00:20:08,164
[SPEAKER_00]: basically, like, you know, school days here in West Medford, field trips to the park, Duggar Park, and the Mystic River.

149
00:20:09,505 --> 00:20:20,514
[SPEAKER_00]: And then, you know, of course, graduate from grade school into what was the Hobbs Middle School in West Medford, which was not there anymore, but it's all the Brooks School now.

150
00:20:20,694 --> 00:20:24,337
[SPEAKER_00]: And of course, like, everyone went up to the high school, so I graduated from there in the late 90s.

151
00:20:27,019 --> 00:20:38,634
[SPEAKER_00]: Even though I lived in my family's home in Medford for some time after high school and into college, when my grandmother passed and we sold the home, I stayed in Medford.

152
00:20:38,814 --> 00:20:40,136
[SPEAKER_00]: There's something about Medford, right?

153
00:20:42,718 --> 00:20:58,161
[SPEAKER_00]: Even when I got married and settled up in Haverhill with my husband at the time, because his kids were in school there, so we settled down there, I was still able to, through my work, it was at the time Brookline Bank, I was still commuting to Medford.

154
00:20:58,963 --> 00:21:08,089
[SPEAKER_00]: I tell you, I would go nowhere else that length of a ride other than Medford because I could say, I leave my house every day and I go home.

155
00:21:09,610 --> 00:21:15,474
[SPEAKER_00]: And especially being in West Medford where I've been in that office now for about 11 years.

156
00:21:16,294 --> 00:21:24,200
[SPEAKER_00]: And the amazing thing was that for many people who walked through the door, I could say, I went to school with you or your kids.

157
00:21:25,621 --> 00:21:29,984
[SPEAKER_00]: And there have just been so many amazing stories I've heard from people coming through to talk.

158
00:21:30,024 --> 00:21:37,989
[SPEAKER_00]: So, like, there's something about Medford that just always pulls you home, and I've always felt very much at home here in West Medford.

159
00:21:38,150 --> 00:21:52,840
[SPEAKER_03]: It's really interesting that you mention how you came from your area of Medford to the Hervey School, because 10 years before Boston got into the kerfluff that they got into about busing,

160
00:21:53,782 --> 00:22:04,005
[SPEAKER_03]: Medford parents voluntarily allowed their kids from the Hervey to be bused to the Gleason, the Waite, and the Dame school to help them achieve racial balance.

161
00:22:04,385 --> 00:22:13,788
[SPEAKER_03]: And it was the first community in Massachusetts that would allow that to happen, where the parents volunteered to let their kids go to these other schools.

162
00:22:14,308 --> 00:22:16,829
[SPEAKER_03]: So it's kind of an interesting paradox.

163
00:22:18,720 --> 00:22:19,501
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, very good.

164
00:22:19,921 --> 00:22:24,164
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, your bank recently changed brands and management.

165
00:22:24,464 --> 00:22:27,567
[SPEAKER_03]: How has that impacted your role as a branch manager?

166
00:22:28,521 --> 00:22:32,964
[SPEAKER_00]: So I refer to it often as same rows, different name.

167
00:22:34,445 --> 00:22:37,406
[SPEAKER_00]: Honestly, my chain of command is largely the same.

168
00:22:38,727 --> 00:22:45,111
[SPEAKER_00]: The former CEO from my old bank corporation is still the CEO in the new organization, same CFO.

169
00:22:45,771 --> 00:22:51,915
[SPEAKER_00]: Our computer system is a little different, but someone had explained to me whenever there's change, there's the phases.

170
00:22:52,175 --> 00:22:55,957
[SPEAKER_00]: So you're informing, you're learning about the change and then

171
00:22:56,453 --> 00:23:01,816
[SPEAKER_00]: storming, the changes upon you, and then you get into norming, where it's normalizing.

172
00:23:01,876 --> 00:23:02,836
[SPEAKER_00]: I think we're getting there now.

173
00:23:03,297 --> 00:23:06,058
[SPEAKER_00]: And then performing, so soon to come, performing.

174
00:23:06,178 --> 00:23:10,180
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, that's training talk, you know, that storming, norming, performing thing.

175
00:23:10,260 --> 00:23:12,942
[SPEAKER_03]: I used to hear about that quite a lot.

176
00:23:15,543 --> 00:23:18,225
[SPEAKER_03]: So Lisa, I wanna ask you about Grant, okay?

177
00:23:18,585 --> 00:23:22,547
[SPEAKER_03]: Because as he, when you came in the door, he came in the door with you.

178
00:23:23,387 --> 00:23:28,497
[SPEAKER_03]: And he's really grown up as a community-centered kid.

179
00:23:29,860 --> 00:23:33,908
[SPEAKER_03]: How do you think his experience has shaped him as a young person?

180
00:23:36,206 --> 00:23:37,066
[SPEAKER_07]: It's amazing.

181
00:23:38,427 --> 00:23:42,747
[SPEAKER_07]: Like I said, my family had a business, so I was always with my parents at work.

182
00:23:42,787 --> 00:23:45,628
[SPEAKER_07]: That's how I understand business and things like that.

183
00:23:46,868 --> 00:23:51,809
[SPEAKER_07]: So it's amazing to have him with me and have that same experience and pass that on to him.

184
00:23:52,949 --> 00:24:01,371
[SPEAKER_07]: But being here, I always tell the story about when we went to Florida, and when we were visiting my mom,

185
00:24:02,871 --> 00:24:20,926
[SPEAKER_07]: It was a senior community and he was the only child and he went down to the pool I let him go with his great aunt and they said Lisa Grant made so many friends He was chatting up all the seniors and they just loved him.

186
00:24:21,006 --> 00:24:22,868
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I love that he

187
00:24:23,761 --> 00:24:25,201
[SPEAKER_07]: He'll have the conversation.

188
00:24:25,261 --> 00:24:28,842
[SPEAKER_07]: A lot of young children are sort of afraid to talk to seniors, right?

189
00:24:29,322 --> 00:24:33,663
[SPEAKER_07]: He's not afraid, and he's learning so much from them.

190
00:24:34,543 --> 00:24:40,345
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think it's just amazing for him to be here, to walk in, to see people that look like him.

191
00:24:40,865 --> 00:24:43,045
[SPEAKER_07]: And we have a wonderful experience in Malden.

192
00:24:43,405 --> 00:24:46,886
[SPEAKER_07]: He goes to Sheppard School, and the same thing there.

193
00:24:47,006 --> 00:24:50,987
[SPEAKER_07]: He's at a super diverse school, and it's just, this is the education that,

194
00:24:52,002 --> 00:24:52,883
[SPEAKER_07]: you dream about.

195
00:24:52,903 --> 00:24:58,527
[SPEAKER_07]: There's intergenerational, interracial, it's just everything.

196
00:24:58,588 --> 00:25:00,769
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm just so blessed to be here.

197
00:25:01,730 --> 00:25:04,192
[SPEAKER_07]: He is turning into a wonderful young man.

198
00:25:04,252 --> 00:25:07,995
[SPEAKER_07]: He's a little scamp, but good fun.

199
00:25:08,015 --> 00:25:15,181
[SPEAKER_07]: And the older men teach him that, like Cecil Fury would teach him good trouble.

200
00:25:15,341 --> 00:25:15,601
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

201
00:25:15,761 --> 00:25:16,021
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

202
00:25:17,437 --> 00:25:22,503
[SPEAKER_03]: So I have taken to calling him LL Cool G. Ladies love little Grant.

203
00:25:23,164 --> 00:25:25,326
[SPEAKER_03]: But he's a good kid.

204
00:25:25,706 --> 00:25:27,629
[SPEAKER_03]: He's a good kid, yeah.

205
00:25:27,869 --> 00:25:33,475
[SPEAKER_03]: And Malin, I want to ask you, if I may, you're a retail banker in Medford.

206
00:25:34,216 --> 00:25:37,380
[SPEAKER_03]: How has that helped you be an advocate for the community center?

207
00:25:38,473 --> 00:25:43,876
[SPEAKER_00]: So in my office, one of the things that I love is the history of that office, right?

208
00:25:43,916 --> 00:25:46,058
[SPEAKER_00]: Because today it's Beacon Bank.

209
00:25:46,478 --> 00:25:48,019
[SPEAKER_00]: Last year it was Brookline Bank.

210
00:25:48,459 --> 00:25:51,361
[SPEAKER_00]: Many years before that, it was Medford Cooperative Bank.

211
00:25:51,481 --> 00:26:00,507
[SPEAKER_00]: But before that, it was the West Medford Cooperative Bank, which blows my mind that one little teeny building was a whole bank.

212
00:26:01,427 --> 00:26:03,128
[SPEAKER_00]: And that bank was formed in the 20s.

213
00:26:06,070 --> 00:26:20,236
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, through the years, and we know the history here in West Medford where families of color were relegated, and when it came to subsidized home loan programs were also largely restricted.

214
00:26:20,877 --> 00:26:27,559
[SPEAKER_00]: So not every bank was lending to families of color, but the West Medford Cooperative Bank was.

215
00:26:28,380 --> 00:26:30,281
[SPEAKER_00]: And so today I see

216
00:26:31,488 --> 00:26:39,413
[SPEAKER_00]: seniors from the neighborhood come through and talk about how when they were little kids, they would come into the bank with their grandparents to pay the mortgage every month.

217
00:26:39,893 --> 00:26:52,320
[SPEAKER_00]: And like, it's stories like that, like the legacy of how the community got to become what it is because there was this peace in the business community that supported that.

218
00:26:53,381 --> 00:26:55,582
[SPEAKER_00]: It makes me really proud to be in that space.

219
00:26:56,343 --> 00:27:05,550
[SPEAKER_03]: It is amazing, and one of your early branch managers, when it was a West Medford Cooperative Bank, he actually served on our board of directors.

220
00:27:05,630 --> 00:27:06,991
[SPEAKER_03]: I can't remember his name.

221
00:27:08,813 --> 00:27:22,083
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, he was a good, and he was a really, really good guy, soft-spoken, but a really, really good leader, and he really helped the community center through some tough years, as you've done, as you've done, no doubt about that.

222
00:27:23,264 --> 00:27:23,824
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, so.

223
00:27:26,652 --> 00:27:37,063
[SPEAKER_03]: We all, as parents, and I am a parent, and I am definitely doing this, what sacrifices have you had to make as a parent in directing this organization?

224
00:27:42,629 --> 00:27:43,811
[SPEAKER_07]: That's a really good question.

225
00:27:45,512 --> 00:27:47,393
[SPEAKER_07]: That's what we keep buying clothes to wear.

226
00:27:47,893 --> 00:27:53,216
[SPEAKER_07]: I've had to make sacrifices, and he's in there now in my office waiting.

227
00:27:53,616 --> 00:27:58,759
[SPEAKER_07]: He came after school, we played in after school, and now he's gotta wait till the end of the night.

228
00:27:58,779 --> 00:28:00,140
[SPEAKER_07]: So we make compromises.

229
00:28:00,160 --> 00:28:06,683
[SPEAKER_07]: So one of the sacrifices, he's got computer time, when I don't want him to have computer time.

230
00:28:06,703 --> 00:28:07,424
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, yeah.

231
00:28:08,024 --> 00:28:11,806
[SPEAKER_07]: Some things, yeah, we sacrifice on the late night.

232
00:28:11,846 --> 00:28:13,447
[SPEAKER_07]: But we make it up in different ways.

233
00:28:14,307 --> 00:28:16,188
[SPEAKER_07]: I've adjusted, so it's not a sacrifice.

234
00:28:16,208 --> 00:28:19,890
[SPEAKER_07]: I just have adjusted my parenting and he's adjusted his kidding.

235
00:28:19,910 --> 00:28:22,071
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh boy.

236
00:28:22,111 --> 00:28:26,413
[SPEAKER_07]: And we've found a way to make it work where it's not a sacrifice.

237
00:28:26,473 --> 00:28:32,936
[SPEAKER_07]: Because if I was sacrificing here with the amount that was going on, I would have been gone a long time ago.

238
00:28:32,996 --> 00:28:35,818
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a heavy weight sitting in that executive role.

239
00:28:37,158 --> 00:28:43,019
[SPEAKER_07]: And so, never one day have I thought that this is a sacrifice or a burden or anything like that.

240
00:28:43,259 --> 00:28:44,500
[SPEAKER_03]: All right, that's a beautiful thing.

241
00:28:45,620 --> 00:28:50,061
[SPEAKER_03]: We're moving into our 90s now as an organization, okay?

242
00:28:50,841 --> 00:28:54,081
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm gonna ask this question of each of you.

243
00:28:54,721 --> 00:29:02,463
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'll ask you first, Lisa, what do you see as the major challenge of the community center as we move into our 90s?

244
00:29:03,957 --> 00:29:05,218
[SPEAKER_07]: Got to pick one challenge.

245
00:29:05,518 --> 00:29:10,400
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, you know, you can pick several, but it's whatever you decide to talk about.

246
00:29:10,420 --> 00:29:14,322
[SPEAKER_07]: What's the major challenge?

247
00:29:14,603 --> 00:29:17,084
[SPEAKER_07]: I think I would say right now,

248
00:29:19,883 --> 00:29:25,185
[SPEAKER_07]: For me, what I view it as is this space, this building, this space.

249
00:29:25,265 --> 00:29:31,788
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's really important to secure the building we're in for the future of our organization.

250
00:29:32,068 --> 00:29:34,529
[SPEAKER_07]: Medford is growing quite rapidly.

251
00:29:35,449 --> 00:29:37,430
[SPEAKER_07]: It's becoming quite an affluent community.

252
00:29:38,270 --> 00:29:51,895
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think that in order to preserve this role that we say we want to be this historic West Medford Community Center, to retain the history of the African American in Medford,

253
00:29:53,376 --> 00:29:55,558
[SPEAKER_07]: that we've really got to secure our location.

254
00:29:55,618 --> 00:29:57,940
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the board understands that.

255
00:29:58,180 --> 00:30:00,382
[SPEAKER_07]: Our membership is beginning to understand that.

256
00:30:00,962 --> 00:30:03,524
[SPEAKER_07]: We have some really great donors that understand that.

257
00:30:03,544 --> 00:30:05,426
[SPEAKER_07]: And we've made investments.

258
00:30:05,466 --> 00:30:07,447
[SPEAKER_07]: You see the floor is done.

259
00:30:07,488 --> 00:30:09,429
[SPEAKER_07]: We've got the walls repainted.

260
00:30:09,469 --> 00:30:11,191
[SPEAKER_07]: We've got new sign out front.

261
00:30:11,211 --> 00:30:16,175
[SPEAKER_07]: And we're working on a lot of things to really invest back in the building.

262
00:30:16,995 --> 00:30:19,938
[SPEAKER_07]: But financially, we really need to secure the building.

263
00:30:20,558 --> 00:30:22,861
[SPEAKER_07]: for the future of this organization.

264
00:30:23,081 --> 00:30:37,977
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, and I know Melinda, part of it, especially looking at it from the aspect of being both a board president and being a banker, what do you see as a major challenge that we're dealing with right now?

265
00:30:39,075 --> 00:30:41,756
[SPEAKER_00]: Honestly, I think sometimes there's just not enough time in the day.

266
00:30:41,776 --> 00:30:42,916
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, okay.

267
00:30:43,196 --> 00:30:45,376
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, there's a lot to do.

268
00:30:45,396 --> 00:30:55,499
[SPEAKER_00]: I know even from, we've gone a long way in terms of making sure that Lisa is not in charge of everything.

269
00:30:56,159 --> 00:31:08,442
[SPEAKER_00]: We've been able to expand staff and make sure that there's more supports and get more community members to attend events and to become members and donors.

270
00:31:10,082 --> 00:31:31,132
[SPEAKER_00]: But there's only so many hours in the day, and there's so many things I think we want to see happen, and great conversations that get started, but it takes capacity to see those things through to, okay, now we have a new fitness instructor, or now we have a particular expert who can come and talk to which group, okay.

271
00:31:31,872 --> 00:31:38,295
[SPEAKER_00]: So it's just there's so much that we want to see happen, and only so much capacity, I guess.

272
00:31:39,183 --> 00:31:41,886
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, all right, that's a good assessment.

273
00:31:42,066 --> 00:31:43,087
[SPEAKER_03]: That's a good assessment.

274
00:31:44,809 --> 00:31:50,196
[SPEAKER_03]: So on the flip side, what are some of the major opportunities you see us having?

275
00:31:52,085 --> 00:31:53,926
[SPEAKER_07]: I think the opportunities are countless.

276
00:31:54,106 --> 00:31:56,526
[SPEAKER_07]: We say this all the time.

277
00:31:56,626 --> 00:31:58,527
[SPEAKER_07]: We don't suffer for a lack of ideas.

278
00:31:59,027 --> 00:32:00,827
[SPEAKER_07]: We definitely don't suffer for a lack of ideas.

279
00:32:00,908 --> 00:32:04,509
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think there's a lot of opportunity, especially in our after school program.

280
00:32:04,529 --> 00:32:06,889
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a wonderful group of children.

281
00:32:07,509 --> 00:32:09,430
[SPEAKER_07]: We have wonderful families that come.

282
00:32:10,390 --> 00:32:15,812
[SPEAKER_07]: At the events, the arts and culture events that we're doing, I think we're just sort of at

283
00:32:17,412 --> 00:32:21,715
[SPEAKER_07]: scratching the surface there, there's a lot more that we can and do plan to do.

284
00:32:21,735 --> 00:32:27,659
[SPEAKER_07]: I think we have a lot more opportunity utilizing the back area.

285
00:32:28,659 --> 00:32:29,740
[SPEAKER_07]: And we have a wonderful board.

286
00:32:29,800 --> 00:32:32,001
[SPEAKER_07]: We have an 11-member board this year.

287
00:32:32,041 --> 00:32:33,222
[SPEAKER_07]: First time in a while.

288
00:32:33,242 --> 00:32:34,863
[SPEAKER_07]: First time in five years.

289
00:32:34,883 --> 00:32:36,944
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're very excited.

290
00:32:36,985 --> 00:32:45,230
[SPEAKER_07]: So there's a lot of opportunity with this board to grow and we're just getting started sort of setting these goals for the next 10 years.

291
00:32:45,950 --> 00:32:47,811
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, Melinda, same question?

292
00:32:49,032 --> 00:32:53,455
[SPEAKER_00]: I couldn't say it any better than Lisa did, truly.

293
00:32:54,975 --> 00:32:59,238
[SPEAKER_03]: You guys are kind of in lockstep, so that's perfectly fine.

294
00:33:00,559 --> 00:33:05,402
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a question that I think I want to ask almost every guest that comes.

295
00:33:06,690 --> 00:33:10,052
[SPEAKER_03]: just because of where we're at as a society right now.

296
00:33:10,492 --> 00:33:22,337
[SPEAKER_03]: So what does the current state of racial reckoning and a growing retreat from healthy dialogue about diversity, equity, and inclusion mean for establishing greater community?

297
00:33:22,497 --> 00:33:27,219
[SPEAKER_03]: I know it's a long question, but if you kind of distill it.

298
00:33:29,540 --> 00:33:30,861
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, yeah.

299
00:33:33,828 --> 00:33:37,749
[SPEAKER_07]: I think that we're not at a new place.

300
00:33:38,329 --> 00:33:40,049
[SPEAKER_07]: We're definitely not at a new place.

301
00:33:40,609 --> 00:33:47,611
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think we suffer for lack of remembering the history.

302
00:33:48,571 --> 00:33:59,073
[SPEAKER_07]: And I know that we've done a lot of, sometimes it's easier to just bite your tongue, hold, you're right.

303
00:34:01,477 --> 00:34:07,005
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, this generation, sort of the gen alpha, I keep telling them, this is an emotional group.

304
00:34:08,387 --> 00:34:10,090
[SPEAKER_07]: This is an emotional group.

305
00:34:10,951 --> 00:34:13,535
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I think that, you know,

306
00:34:15,053 --> 00:34:18,354
[SPEAKER_07]: Grace is a big thing that I've learned, right?

307
00:34:18,374 --> 00:34:18,734
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes.

308
00:34:19,554 --> 00:34:24,956
[SPEAKER_07]: And that, yeah, it just, it goes beyond how we feel.

309
00:34:24,976 --> 00:34:36,080
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it goes beyond how we feel, and I think it's time for a lot of folks, I often say, you know, you need to take off your lenses, and I need you to put in my lenses from the center, from our point of view.

310
00:34:36,160 --> 00:34:39,821
[SPEAKER_07]: Put these lenses on, okay, and now let's have our conversation from this point of view.

311
00:34:41,042 --> 00:34:50,009
[SPEAKER_07]: Because a lot of times I can speak directly as sort of the executive director of the historic black organization.

312
00:34:50,998 --> 00:34:58,121
[SPEAKER_07]: hear that there's times when I feel the voice shrinking and being snuffed out.

313
00:34:59,581 --> 00:35:04,103
[SPEAKER_07]: There's times where we've got to carry a big stick.

314
00:35:05,104 --> 00:35:14,828
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think we're at a point where we've done a lot of cow tailing to move the process forward, to get things done.

315
00:35:16,129 --> 00:35:18,192
[SPEAKER_07]: But we've taken that sort of as far as we can go.

316
00:35:18,232 --> 00:35:21,097
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think it's time, look, we really need to put up the mirror.

317
00:35:21,678 --> 00:35:23,081
[SPEAKER_07]: We need to have these conversations.

318
00:35:23,121 --> 00:35:24,744
[SPEAKER_07]: Let's have the conversations so then.

319
00:35:25,703 --> 00:35:31,028
[SPEAKER_07]: we can deal with the emotionality of it, and then let's walk it forward, right?

320
00:35:31,068 --> 00:35:35,913
[SPEAKER_07]: Because we're doing a lot of time spinning in emotion, we're not solving anything.

321
00:35:36,714 --> 00:35:49,387
[SPEAKER_07]: And sometimes when you're in a highly intellectual community that we love to talk about problems, we love to talk about how we got here, and the sociology of it, and why it's

322
00:35:49,926 --> 00:35:51,747
[SPEAKER_07]: But then we never solve anything, right?

323
00:35:51,807 --> 00:35:56,491
[SPEAKER_07]: We get caught up in the accolades of, well, we've discussed that.

324
00:35:58,252 --> 00:36:03,896
[SPEAKER_07]: The problem is we've got to get to solving that because we're just passing it down, passing it down, passing it down.

325
00:36:03,916 --> 00:36:05,317
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think

326
00:36:06,705 --> 00:36:11,527
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes, families need to have these conversations, but we don't sit at the dinner table anymore.

327
00:36:11,547 --> 00:36:13,788
[SPEAKER_07]: And when we do, we're often on our phones.

328
00:36:14,429 --> 00:36:22,712
[SPEAKER_07]: And we don't take the walk as a family any longer and have those conversations or come back and do that.

329
00:36:23,213 --> 00:36:27,835
[SPEAKER_07]: A lot of us are just decompressing and we want to turn on the TV or watch our favorite video.

330
00:36:28,630 --> 00:36:38,761
[SPEAKER_07]: And it's a lot easier, and we pass it on to the next day, but again, we're dealing with passing it on, and we see that it's compiled, and so, yes.

331
00:36:40,263 --> 00:36:47,951
[SPEAKER_03]: It's interesting, because it was one of the reasons why I loved having the conversation, beginning to have the conversation that we had last month,

332
00:36:48,502 --> 00:36:55,524
[SPEAKER_03]: with Smitty, Stephen Smith, and the elephant in the room, because it's exactly what you're talking about.

333
00:36:55,544 --> 00:37:02,445
[SPEAKER_03]: It's the elephant in the room, and we keep walking by it, we keep seeing it, and we know it's there, but we're not addressing it.

334
00:37:03,085 --> 00:37:10,847
[SPEAKER_03]: And when we do address it, we're addressing it, we put the kid gloves on, and we speak softly.

335
00:37:11,187 --> 00:37:15,829
[SPEAKER_03]: Sometimes we carry a big stick, sometimes we go empty-handed and we're not able to do anything about it.

336
00:37:21,711 --> 00:37:27,213
[SPEAKER_03]: There's some depth to that and there's some additional conversation that we'll have, I'm sure, over time.

337
00:37:29,113 --> 00:37:39,797
[SPEAKER_03]: So I want to go to working here or supporting this organization right now, what are you most thankful for?

338
00:37:41,631 --> 00:37:56,697
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm most thankful for the opportunity to serve, truly, because there's a quote I think I delivered at an event once before where it says, you make a living by what you receive, but you make a life by what you give.

339
00:37:56,717 --> 00:37:56,797
[SPEAKER_00]: Wow.

340
00:37:59,598 --> 00:38:14,743
[SPEAKER_00]: Even in the business that I do, and this is probably not the way most people in a capital business would approach the work, but I don't think about it in terms of what can I get?

341
00:38:15,743 --> 00:38:19,744
[SPEAKER_00]: What numbers can I make or what achievements can I achieve?

342
00:38:19,824 --> 00:38:23,185
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think of it in terms of what am I responsible for?

343
00:38:26,886 --> 00:38:30,128
[SPEAKER_00]: I guess I don't know if I'm quite answering your question.

344
00:38:30,148 --> 00:38:31,069
[SPEAKER_00]: I think you are.

345
00:38:31,189 --> 00:38:39,834
[SPEAKER_00]: I think it's important because in the time that I've been a member of the center, which goes back to I think like 2016-17, I came on board as a member.

346
00:38:39,854 --> 00:38:45,238
[SPEAKER_00]: Then in 2019, I think it was, I was invited onto the board.

347
00:38:50,683 --> 00:39:01,238
[SPEAKER_00]: and began the work, and at the time I took on the treasurer role, and then the opportunity to serve as the board president came through.

348
00:39:01,950 --> 00:39:09,214
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, I hope there's a point in time where someone says, I want to take on that mantle, and I'd be glad to shepherd.

349
00:39:10,595 --> 00:39:15,338
[SPEAKER_00]: I always want to be a support to this organization.

350
00:39:15,398 --> 00:39:23,243
[SPEAKER_00]: So whether that's attending events, or monetary donation, or showing up to volunteer to do yard cleanup,

351
00:39:24,083 --> 00:39:30,727
[SPEAKER_00]: bring my husband down to help with the IT support, or to buy a brick for the brick installation.

352
00:39:30,888 --> 00:39:37,292
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, and this center, I mean, there's a lot of memories that I hold from when I became a member.

353
00:39:37,352 --> 00:39:41,154
[SPEAKER_00]: Some amazing productions and performances that happened here.

354
00:39:41,174 --> 00:39:44,576
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, sometimes things of a caliber that you would be

355
00:39:45,777 --> 00:39:57,001
[SPEAKER_00]: paying top dollar at a big music hall or something of that nature where you get to come here and in the community and surrounded by friends and neighbors get these beautiful gems.

356
00:39:57,581 --> 00:40:02,143
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it's just been so much that I'm thankful for here, truly.

357
00:40:02,163 --> 00:40:03,344
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good, very good.

358
00:40:03,804 --> 00:40:04,804
[SPEAKER_03]: Same question, Lisa?

359
00:40:07,085 --> 00:40:10,946
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, yeah.

360
00:40:11,567 --> 00:40:14,928
[SPEAKER_07]: I am thankful for all the people

361
00:40:15,842 --> 00:40:16,782
[SPEAKER_07]: that I get to meet.

362
00:40:18,263 --> 00:40:22,185
[SPEAKER_07]: It would be easier to get my job done if I just came in and shut the door.

363
00:40:24,005 --> 00:40:29,187
[SPEAKER_07]: But that is not what membership is about and that's not what community is about.

364
00:40:29,367 --> 00:40:39,452
[SPEAKER_07]: So I've gotten to know so many people and I know intimate details about their life and their children and their grandchildren and their great-grands.

365
00:40:42,065 --> 00:40:46,189
[SPEAKER_07]: And even when people are having a hard day, they know they can come into the office.

366
00:40:46,910 --> 00:40:53,836
[SPEAKER_07]: If they need a resource, they come into the office, they understand they'll be handled with respect and care and privacy.

367
00:40:56,118 --> 00:40:59,922
[SPEAKER_07]: So I'm grateful to know a lot of these people, people who are on the wall.

368
00:41:01,302 --> 00:41:19,430
[SPEAKER_07]: to know their stories, they've touched my heart, they've touched my family, and that's what I'm most grateful for, to come to the table at the board meeting and see them getting things done, and what should we do next, and working with you, and yeah, everything is just great.

369
00:41:19,470 --> 00:41:22,492
[SPEAKER_07]: The kids, working with the kids, I swore I was done with it.

370
00:41:23,752 --> 00:41:27,433
[SPEAKER_07]: Every time you get away, they drag you back in, but it's a great group of kids.

371
00:41:27,453 --> 00:41:30,174
[SPEAKER_07]: They have a lot of energy, and it's just wonderful.

372
00:41:30,194 --> 00:41:32,355
[SPEAKER_07]: And every day, I'm thankful.

373
00:41:33,035 --> 00:41:33,475
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good.

374
00:41:34,095 --> 00:41:34,535
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good.

375
00:41:34,595 --> 00:41:40,417
[SPEAKER_03]: OK, so a couple quick things before we close down.

376
00:41:41,237 --> 00:41:43,878
[SPEAKER_03]: Life at the WMCC, that's how I term it.

377
00:41:44,478 --> 00:41:46,159
[SPEAKER_03]: What is always funny to you?

378
00:41:48,860 --> 00:41:49,780
[SPEAKER_07]: Life at WMCC?

379
00:41:51,293 --> 00:41:52,654
[SPEAKER_07]: How about West Memphis in general?

380
00:41:52,714 --> 00:41:54,516
[SPEAKER_07]: But what's always funny?

381
00:41:54,596 --> 00:41:56,297
[SPEAKER_07]: The seniors are always funny.

382
00:41:58,940 --> 00:42:00,741
[SPEAKER_07]: The seniors are always funny.

383
00:42:00,781 --> 00:42:02,743
[SPEAKER_07]: We would have a hit.

384
00:42:03,664 --> 00:42:06,046
[SPEAKER_07]: We would have a YouTube sensation.

385
00:42:06,146 --> 00:42:07,066
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, no doubt about it.

386
00:42:07,146 --> 00:42:08,107
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, absolutely.

387
00:42:08,347 --> 00:42:08,908
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely.

388
00:42:08,988 --> 00:42:11,890
[SPEAKER_07]: With the shenanigans, the conversations.

389
00:42:12,431 --> 00:42:16,014
[SPEAKER_07]: I never knew that life in your senior years could be so fun.

390
00:42:16,074 --> 00:42:18,636
[SPEAKER_07]: It could be so funny that you could still be fit.

391
00:42:19,737 --> 00:42:27,368
[SPEAKER_07]: So that is always so funny to me and how similar the seniors and the kids are.

392
00:42:29,367 --> 00:42:46,965
[SPEAKER_07]: with their cake and ice cream, again, being loud and rowdy, having to ask them to leave, maybe you gotta get the senior's kid to come and get them, and the kids, you gotta get their parents to come and get them, so there's a lot of similarities and through lines there that I love.

393
00:42:47,346 --> 00:42:52,251
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, Melinda, life at the WMCC, what never ceases to amaze you?

394
00:42:53,168 --> 00:43:02,793
[SPEAKER_00]: The way people come together and offer help, whether that's like a helping hand or a needed item, a service, a dollar.

395
00:43:02,933 --> 00:43:09,276
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, these are all, it does amaze me that there's, I mean, and I shouldn't be amazed because it's an amazing community, right?

396
00:43:10,036 --> 00:43:15,959
[SPEAKER_00]: That there's so much support for the center and we wouldn't be here without the support of our members and neighbors.

397
00:43:16,379 --> 00:43:18,060
[SPEAKER_03]: Absolutely, absolutely, okay.

398
00:43:18,996 --> 00:43:20,037
[SPEAKER_03]: Easy one, maybe.

399
00:43:20,678 --> 00:43:23,941
[SPEAKER_03]: Life at the WMCC, what sometimes keeps you up at night?

400
00:43:25,002 --> 00:43:25,383
[SPEAKER_07]: Nothing.

401
00:43:26,284 --> 00:43:27,785
[SPEAKER_07]: Nothing keeps me up at night.

402
00:43:28,286 --> 00:43:33,010
[SPEAKER_07]: I swore when I came into this job, I wouldn't take work home like that.

403
00:43:33,030 --> 00:43:34,612
[SPEAKER_07]: I wouldn't be stressed.

404
00:43:34,652 --> 00:43:38,176
[SPEAKER_07]: So I often say my help comes from above.

405
00:43:38,396 --> 00:43:40,118
[SPEAKER_07]: So I don't take.

406
00:43:41,187 --> 00:43:43,309
[SPEAKER_07]: anything home and it doesn't keep me up at night, okay?

407
00:43:43,509 --> 00:43:45,690
[SPEAKER_03]: I love that answer, I really do, I really do.

408
00:43:45,970 --> 00:43:51,634
[SPEAKER_03]: I probably expected something different, but I really do love that answer.

409
00:43:53,115 --> 00:43:55,517
[SPEAKER_03]: Life at the WMCC, what keeps you up at night?

410
00:43:56,682 --> 00:44:00,486
[SPEAKER_00]: Honestly, it's my brain playing a jukebox at 3 a.m.

411
00:44:00,526 --> 00:44:04,931
[SPEAKER_00]: No, I will tell you, I actually had a dream and I told Lisa about this.

412
00:44:05,191 --> 00:44:07,613
[SPEAKER_00]: I woke up kind of in a panic after having this dream.

413
00:44:07,653 --> 00:44:15,041
[SPEAKER_00]: My dream involved, I was here at the center and I was sitting at a board table and there were people there that I was supposed to know.

414
00:44:15,081 --> 00:44:17,183
[SPEAKER_00]: They were officially like the new people in charge.

415
00:44:17,783 --> 00:44:19,744
[SPEAKER_00]: And I was like, where's Lisa?

416
00:44:19,804 --> 00:44:21,125
[SPEAKER_00]: Is Lisa even here anymore?

417
00:44:21,305 --> 00:44:21,806
[SPEAKER_00]: What happened?

418
00:44:21,866 --> 00:44:22,466
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh my goodness.

419
00:44:22,866 --> 00:44:28,550
[SPEAKER_00]: And then their question to me was, tell us about this expenditure that happened in 2008.

420
00:44:28,990 --> 00:44:31,152
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'm like, I wasn't even here.

421
00:44:31,232 --> 00:44:31,992
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know about it.

422
00:44:32,032 --> 00:44:34,894
[SPEAKER_00]: And I woke up, and I was kind of in a panic.

423
00:44:34,934 --> 00:44:36,415
[SPEAKER_00]: I was like, Lisa, oh my god.

424
00:44:36,455 --> 00:44:37,235
[SPEAKER_00]: And I was like, wait, no.

425
00:44:37,736 --> 00:44:38,396
[SPEAKER_00]: Lisa's still here.

426
00:44:38,876 --> 00:44:39,597
[SPEAKER_00]: Everything's OK.

427
00:44:40,177 --> 00:44:42,699
[SPEAKER_00]: But I mean, because we're in good hands here.

428
00:44:42,759 --> 00:44:44,060
[SPEAKER_00]: We're in really good hands here.

429
00:44:44,080 --> 00:44:45,000
[SPEAKER_00]: I love that.

430
00:44:45,160 --> 00:44:45,561
[SPEAKER_03]: I love that.

431
00:44:46,941 --> 00:45:00,631
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, so ten years from now, as we turn 100 as a community-based organization, what will you want the people of Medford to know about the center and the space that's been created?

432
00:45:03,153 --> 00:45:05,055
[SPEAKER_07]: That is a challenging question.

433
00:45:06,689 --> 00:45:10,410
[SPEAKER_07]: So I need more time for that.

434
00:45:11,130 --> 00:45:16,232
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, what I would want the people of Medford to know that this is here because of them.

435
00:45:16,752 --> 00:45:23,494
[SPEAKER_07]: We are deemed the West Medford Community Center, West Medfordites got it going.

436
00:45:23,574 --> 00:45:32,097
[SPEAKER_07]: It certainly serves primarily West Medford because they're within walking distance than they have, but the doors are open to everyone, it belongs.

437
00:45:32,757 --> 00:45:38,019
[SPEAKER_07]: to the community, and oftentimes I say that, I'm from Malden, this belongs to you all.

438
00:45:39,260 --> 00:45:49,363
[SPEAKER_07]: So yeah, I would want them to know what a dynamic business it is, because there's not many businesses that survive after 100 years.

439
00:45:50,364 --> 00:45:52,805
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think it's just a special gem.

440
00:45:53,085 --> 00:45:58,247
[SPEAKER_07]: It's just unfortunate in Medford, there is a lot of history, it sort of overshadows

441
00:45:58,907 --> 00:46:19,293
[SPEAKER_07]: what we have here, but it is no less important, it is no less dynamic, that there are wonderful, great people that have come through here, that go on to inspire the next generation, and that you can still be a part of it, you should be a part of it, your kids should be a part of it, and there's a place for you.

442
00:46:19,533 --> 00:46:21,093
[SPEAKER_03]: That's right, that's right, that's right.

443
00:46:21,573 --> 00:46:26,575
[SPEAKER_03]: All right, let me ask you the same question with a twist.

444
00:46:28,427 --> 00:46:43,649
[SPEAKER_03]: As someone who grew up in Medford and saw both sides of, you know, of Medford, so to speak, what would you want the people of Medford to know about the community center at 100 Years?

445
00:46:45,758 --> 00:46:47,879
[SPEAKER_00]: I would want them to know what our mission is.

446
00:46:48,559 --> 00:47:01,705
[SPEAKER_00]: The mission of the West Medford Community Center is to connect the diverse people of Medford and the greater Mystic Valley region through our educational and cultural

447
00:47:02,275 --> 00:47:06,177
[SPEAKER_00]: and all of the types of programs and services we do.

448
00:47:06,698 --> 00:47:08,599
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's what I would want people to know.

449
00:47:08,619 --> 00:47:09,940
[SPEAKER_03]: I love that.

450
00:47:10,020 --> 00:47:11,000
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good, very good.

451
00:47:11,281 --> 00:47:15,903
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, what would people who are just meeting you for the first time be surprised to learn about you?

452
00:47:15,923 --> 00:47:17,724
[SPEAKER_07]: Oh, gosh.

453
00:47:23,657 --> 00:47:24,777
[SPEAKER_07]: Why did you ask me that?

454
00:47:24,797 --> 00:47:25,958
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know.

455
00:47:26,958 --> 00:47:31,799
[SPEAKER_07]: They will be surprised to know that I love basketball.

456
00:47:31,859 --> 00:47:33,460
[SPEAKER_07]: I was a tomboy.

457
00:47:33,620 --> 00:47:40,182
[SPEAKER_07]: I was never a girl who put on matching clothes and jewelry and things like that.

458
00:47:40,882 --> 00:47:42,402
[SPEAKER_07]: Played basketball all the time.

459
00:47:42,863 --> 00:47:44,683
[SPEAKER_07]: One year in high school, I wore shorts.

460
00:47:45,503 --> 00:47:50,725
[SPEAKER_07]: It was like that blizzard we had in April, but I dug down and I wore those shorts.

461
00:47:51,713 --> 00:47:53,895
[SPEAKER_07]: Because I didn't want my parents to be right.

462
00:47:54,755 --> 00:47:55,016
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah.

463
00:47:56,237 --> 00:47:57,598
[SPEAKER_07]: So I love basketball.

464
00:47:57,678 --> 00:47:59,239
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm a coach at heart.

465
00:47:59,299 --> 00:48:00,240
[SPEAKER_07]: I've refereed.

466
00:48:00,280 --> 00:48:03,162
[SPEAKER_07]: I've been a basketball official for over 10 years.

467
00:48:04,263 --> 00:48:07,965
[SPEAKER_07]: Coached boys basketball primarily in Fitchburg.

468
00:48:07,985 --> 00:48:10,848
[SPEAKER_07]: Did AAU basketball, traveled a lot.

469
00:48:10,948 --> 00:48:14,711
[SPEAKER_07]: Had a lot of young folks go on to do big things in college.

470
00:48:14,791 --> 00:48:17,773
[SPEAKER_07]: And so, yeah, I think people will be surprised.

471
00:48:17,953 --> 00:48:21,356
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, now see, that's exactly what I thought you might say.

472
00:48:21,856 --> 00:48:24,799
[SPEAKER_03]: That's what I would have said about you.

473
00:48:25,039 --> 00:48:25,760
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, you know me.

474
00:48:26,180 --> 00:48:27,561
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, y'all don't know Lisa.

475
00:48:27,601 --> 00:48:28,943
[SPEAKER_03]: Lisa's a hooper.

476
00:48:28,983 --> 00:48:30,104
[SPEAKER_03]: She's a hooper, you know.

477
00:48:30,124 --> 00:48:31,445
[SPEAKER_03]: She can go left, she can go right.

478
00:48:31,745 --> 00:48:34,467
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, don't get it twisted.

479
00:48:34,508 --> 00:48:35,749
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, she can play, right?

480
00:48:35,769 --> 00:48:38,311
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, I learned my lesson a few years ago.

481
00:48:38,331 --> 00:48:40,933
[SPEAKER_07]: I used to play with the kids all the time.

482
00:48:40,993 --> 00:48:45,037
[SPEAKER_07]: I had a gym in Fitchburg, and I used to play all the time and take them one-on-one.

483
00:48:45,648 --> 00:48:49,091
[SPEAKER_07]: and trying to beat Lisa was a thing until one year I had one kid.

484
00:48:49,431 --> 00:48:53,395
[SPEAKER_07]: We trained him up so good, this kid crossed me up so hard.

485
00:48:53,795 --> 00:48:58,459
[SPEAKER_07]: He, my knee buckle, and the whole gym went crazy.

486
00:48:58,519 --> 00:49:00,240
[SPEAKER_03]: I said never again, never again, yeah.

487
00:49:03,703 --> 00:49:04,964
[SPEAKER_03]: That's fantastic.

488
00:49:06,364 --> 00:49:10,866
[SPEAKER_03]: Melinda, what, people meeting you for the first time, what would they be surprised to learn about you?

489
00:49:11,507 --> 00:49:13,507
[SPEAKER_00]: So, I was not into athletics.

490
00:49:13,728 --> 00:49:16,509
[SPEAKER_00]: When I went to school, marching band was my sport.

491
00:49:17,349 --> 00:49:19,270
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm a musician, still today.

492
00:49:19,290 --> 00:49:20,791
[SPEAKER_00]: I grew in Medford Public.

493
00:49:20,971 --> 00:49:23,852
[SPEAKER_00]: I started in middle school playing the clarinet.

494
00:49:24,312 --> 00:49:24,832
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh my goodness.

495
00:49:24,972 --> 00:49:36,118
[SPEAKER_00]: And as I went up through middle school, high school, all involved in the bands and the orchestra, even in jazz band, where they actually didn't need clarinet players, but they did need trombones.

496
00:49:36,178 --> 00:49:40,220
[SPEAKER_00]: So they said to me, another kid who played clarinet and a girl who played the flute, you're the trombone section.

497
00:49:40,300 --> 00:49:40,980
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh my goodness.

498
00:49:41,040 --> 00:49:41,861
[SPEAKER_00]: So got to pick that up.

499
00:49:42,561 --> 00:49:46,463
[SPEAKER_00]: And then all through college, I actually went to school and got a degree in music.

500
00:49:47,063 --> 00:49:50,025
[SPEAKER_00]: And here I am, 21 years as a banker, right?

501
00:49:50,926 --> 00:49:54,669
[SPEAKER_00]: And I still to this day, I play in a community marching band.

502
00:49:55,429 --> 00:50:00,733
[SPEAKER_00]: And we do a lot of the festivals in the North End where they do the processions with the saints and stuff.

503
00:50:00,933 --> 00:50:02,775
[SPEAKER_03]: Shoot, I would have told you to bring your clarinet.

504
00:50:02,795 --> 00:50:07,698
[SPEAKER_00]: You could have played with... I'm good enough for community marching band.

505
00:50:08,459 --> 00:50:09,480
[SPEAKER_00]: I am no virtuoso.

506
00:50:10,597 --> 00:50:12,378
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, that's fantastic.

507
00:50:12,919 --> 00:50:16,681
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay, so I wanna give you both a last word.

508
00:50:17,222 --> 00:50:20,164
[SPEAKER_03]: What would be your parting thoughts on the evening, Lise?

509
00:50:20,944 --> 00:50:28,169
[SPEAKER_07]: I would just say, I would wanna say I'm very humbled by the community that I've experienced here.

510
00:50:28,690 --> 00:50:31,091
[SPEAKER_07]: That has kind of been a through line in my career.

511
00:50:32,172 --> 00:50:35,755
[SPEAKER_07]: And so it's special to come to a place that's sort of already established.

512
00:50:36,335 --> 00:50:38,277
[SPEAKER_07]: trying to rebuild and rebrand.

513
00:50:39,017 --> 00:50:55,331
[SPEAKER_07]: But I am very thankful to all our donors, our sponsors, our members, many who are in the room, to Tufts University, the City of Medford, Mystic River Watershed Association, NAACP.

514
00:50:55,351 --> 00:50:58,093
[SPEAKER_07]: This is a place where you

515
00:51:02,677 --> 00:51:04,679
[SPEAKER_07]: you don't get much recognition, right?

516
00:51:04,739 --> 00:51:06,140
[SPEAKER_07]: There's a lot of work to do.

517
00:51:06,160 --> 00:51:09,923
[SPEAKER_07]: And everybody does the work.

518
00:51:10,704 --> 00:51:16,669
[SPEAKER_07]: And if you're coming to help, if you're coming to get accolades, this is probably not the place to come.

519
00:51:18,820 --> 00:51:24,322
[SPEAKER_07]: But with that being said, I want to make sure people know that we are very grateful for them.

520
00:51:24,602 --> 00:51:26,023
[SPEAKER_07]: We are so thankful for them.

521
00:51:26,603 --> 00:51:31,204
[SPEAKER_07]: We're doing a better job of recognizing folks, but it's kind of like you come here and do the work.

522
00:51:31,264 --> 00:51:32,225
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, we all do the work.

523
00:51:34,508 --> 00:51:37,149
[SPEAKER_07]: But yes, thank you to our donor sponsors.

524
00:51:37,169 --> 00:51:40,750
[SPEAKER_07]: Our board emeritus, Rachel Tanner, who's out there.

525
00:51:41,090 --> 00:51:43,830
[SPEAKER_07]: Our board members who are not here.

526
00:51:44,430 --> 00:51:45,771
[SPEAKER_07]: They've been fantastic.

527
00:51:45,811 --> 00:51:47,971
[SPEAKER_07]: And you, Terry.

528
00:51:48,471 --> 00:51:52,912
[SPEAKER_07]: Terry carries a great weight of this center as well, day in and day out.

529
00:51:52,992 --> 00:51:55,633
[SPEAKER_07]: And so I'm very thankful for you as well.

530
00:51:55,653 --> 00:51:57,974
[SPEAKER_02]: We're trying.

531
00:51:59,274 --> 00:51:59,874
[SPEAKER_03]: We're trying.

532
00:52:01,594 --> 00:52:03,755
[SPEAKER_03]: What about you, Melinda, your last words on?

533
00:52:04,315 --> 00:52:07,798
[SPEAKER_00]: So I want to tell people or ask people, don't be shy.

534
00:52:08,498 --> 00:52:13,182
[SPEAKER_00]: Like when it comes to, especially when it comes to, if you're wondering, like, how can I support?

535
00:52:13,242 --> 00:52:18,286
[SPEAKER_00]: Because if you do or don't have dollars in your own pocket, that doesn't mean you can't help, right?

536
00:52:18,567 --> 00:52:19,828
[SPEAKER_00]: That's maybe too many double negatives.

537
00:52:19,908 --> 00:52:22,690
[SPEAKER_00]: But like, I'll give an example.

538
00:52:23,430 --> 00:52:30,116
[SPEAKER_00]: When there was a little bit of a pinch at a point in time during the calendar year where just all the bills have to be paid at that point in time.

539
00:52:30,687 --> 00:52:34,128
[SPEAKER_00]: I reached out to friends and family, and I said, get creative.

540
00:52:34,568 --> 00:52:45,372
[SPEAKER_00]: So my aunt baked a whole bunch of baked goods, brought them to her office, and said, this is a bake sale, you're buying cookies, you're buying whatever, and you're donating to the community center.

541
00:52:46,272 --> 00:52:55,875
[SPEAKER_00]: My mom, who is a jewelry artist, has consistently donated her works, where if you are inspired to take a piece, it's like, take a piece, make a donation.

542
00:52:57,435 --> 00:53:13,281
[SPEAKER_00]: whether it's, you can Facebook fundraise, you can, if you really want to get involved and rent the space out or do a fundraising event, I think we can even work out like deep, deep, deep discounts on the rental if it's a fundraising event.

543
00:53:14,561 --> 00:53:20,123
[SPEAKER_00]: I would just ask folks to be creative because there are so many ways that you can support the center.

544
00:53:20,703 --> 00:53:23,064
[SPEAKER_03]: That's perfect, that's a perfect last word on it.

545
00:53:23,813 --> 00:53:31,277
[SPEAKER_03]: So, thank you both for bringing your perspectives and your best wishes for this cultural oasis in greater Medford.

546
00:53:31,737 --> 00:53:46,545
[SPEAKER_03]: It really does remain a great treasure, and we do have a daunting challenge, because we've inherited its preservation and its development, and, you know, where we go and what we do will say a lot about where we go and what we do.

547
00:53:47,657 --> 00:53:54,503
[SPEAKER_03]: And to our audience, both here and elsewhere, thanks so much for your attentiveness and your interest in our discussion.

548
00:53:54,883 --> 00:54:04,210
[SPEAKER_03]: And thanks for coming with us as we continue to refresh for greater flexibility in bringing the best stories and entertainment possible to you.

549
00:54:04,951 --> 00:54:09,137
[SPEAKER_03]: Please get ready for something very special on the musical side of the coin.

550
00:54:09,458 --> 00:54:20,294
[SPEAKER_03]: We're gonna take a few minutes to reset the stage, and then I'll come back and share some WMCC announcements, and then we'll have our musical entertainment for the evening.

